{"title_page": "Istanbul Airport", "text_new": "{{Distinguish||text=[[Istanbul Atat\u00fcrk Airport]], which is now serving cargo and general aviation flights, and [[Istanbul Sabiha G\u00f6k\u00e7en International Airport]], another important airport of Istanbul}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox airport\n| name = Istanbul Airport\n| nativename = {{small|''{{lang|tr|\u0130stanbul Havaliman\u0131}}''}}\n| nativename-a = \n| nativename-r = \n| image = \u0130GA Havaliman\u0131 \u0130\u015fletmesi A.\u015e. logo.svg\n| image-width = 100\n| image2 = \u0130stanbul Yeni Havaliman\u0131 airport Dec 2019.jpg\n| image2-width = 300\n| image2_alt = \n| caption2 = \n| FAA = \n| TC = \n| LID = \n| WMO = \n| IATA = IST\n| ICAO = LTFM\n| GPS = \n| type = Public\n| owner-oper = \n| owner = [[General Directorate of State Airports|General Directorate of State Airports (DHM\u0130)]]\n| operator = IGA (Istanbul Grand Airport) Havaliman\u0131 \u0130\u015fletmesi [[S.A. (corporation)|A.\u015e.]]\n| city-served = [[Istanbul]], [[Turkey]]\n| location = [[Arnavutk\u00f6y (district)|Arnavutk\u00f6y]], [[Istanbul]]\n| opened = {{Start date|2018|10|29|df=yes}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/economy/istanbul-airport-worlds-new-hub-officially-opened/1296955|title=Istanbul Airport, 'world's new hub,' officially opened|website=www.aa.com.tr}}</ref>\n| hub = * [[Onur Air]] \n* [[Turkish Airlines]]\n| focus_city = \n| timezone = [[Time in Turkey|TRT]]\n| metric-elev = yes\n| metric-rwy = yes\n| elevation-m = 99\n| utc = [[UTC+03:00]]\n| elevation-f = 325\n| coordinates = {{coord|41|15|44|N|28|43|40|E|region:TR-34_type:airport|display=it}}\n| website = {{Official URL}}\n| image_map = \n| image_map_caption = \n| pushpin_map = Istanbul#Turkey#Europe\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location of airport\n| r1-number = 16L/34R\n| r1-length-m = 3,750\n| r1-surface = [[Asphalt]]\n| r2-length-m = 3,750\n| r3-length-m = 4,100\n| r4-length-m = 4,100\n| r5-length-m = \n| r6-length-m = \n| h1-number = \n| h1-length-m = \n| h1-surface = <!-- up to h12 -->\n| stat-year = 2019\n| stat1-header = Total passengers\n| stat1-data = 52,578,008\n| stat2-header = International passengers\n| stat2-data = 39,857,182\n| stat3-header = Aircraft Operations\n| stat3-data = 329,799\n| stat4-header = Cargo tonnage\n| stat4-data = 852,943\n| footnotes = Source: (Turkish AIP at Eurocontrol) Turkey<ref name=\"aip_ltba\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dhmi.gov.tr/sayfalar/istatistik.aspx|title=General Directorate Of State Airports Authority|accessdate=February 9, 2020}}</ref>\n| r2-number = 16R/34L\n| r3-number = 17L/35R\n| r4-number = 17R/35L\n| r5-number = \n| r6-number = \n| r2-surface = Asphalt\n| r3-surface = Asphalt\n| r4-surface = Asphalt\n}}\n\n'''Istanbul Airport''' {{Airport codes|IST|LTFM}} ({{lang-tr|\u0130stanbul Havaliman\u0131}})<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ntv.com.tr/galeri/turkiye/yeni-havalimaninin-adi-belli-oldu-istanbul-havalimani-tabelalari-asildi,uQweIzQJuEO5By59Eg4xnw|title=Yeni havaliman\u0131n\u0131n ad\u0131 belli oldu (\u0130stanbul Havaliman\u0131 tabelalar\u0131 as\u0131ld\u0131)|website=NTV}}</ref> is the main [[international airport]] serving [[Istanbul]], [[Turkey]]. It is located in the [[Arnavutk\u00f6y (district)|Arnavutk\u00f6y]] district on the [[Europe]]an side of the city.\n\nAll scheduled [[Commercial aviation|commercial passenger flights]] were transferred from [[Istanbul Atat\u00fcrk Airport]] to Istanbul Airport on April 6, 2019, following the closure of Istanbul Atat\u00fcrk Airport for scheduled passenger flights.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-turkey-airport/last-flight-leaves-ataturk-as-istanbul-switches-airports-idUSKCN1RI0CY|title=Last flight leaves Ataturk as Istanbul switches airports|website=Reuters}}</ref> The [[IATA code|IATA airport code]] IST was also transferred to the new airport.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://atwonline.com/airports-routes/turkish-airlines-relocates-new-istanbul-airport|title=Turkish Airlines relocates to new Istanbul Airport|publisher=ATWOnline|date=5 April 2019}}</ref> Once all phases are completed by mid-2020s, the airport will be able to accommodate 200 million passengers a year.<ref>{{cite news|title=Turkish Airlines is switching to a new Istanbul airport \u2013 all in 45 hours|date=6 April 2019|url=https://www.theguardian.com/cities/2019/apr/06/turkish-airlines-switching-to-new-airport-all-in-45-hours|work=Guardian|access-date=13 April 2019|quote=The opening date has been pushed back three times, but authorities insist that the main terminal building and two runways will be fully operational by Sunday, in what critics say it is a rushed and dangerous attempt to stay on schedule.}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[File:\u0130stanbul_Havaliman\u0131_Airport_2019_19.jpg|thumb|Terminal building exterior]]\n[[File:Istanbul_Airport_inside_hall.jpg|thumb|Check-in area interior]]\n[[File:Istanbul_Airport,_Arnavutk\u00f6y_(P1090186).jpg|thumb|Airside area interior]]\n\n=== Background ===\nDue to a lack of space to construct an additional runway at [[Istanbul Atat\u00fcrk Airport]], airport growth being restricted due to the growth of the city, the Turkish Airport Authority not allowing additional [[Cargo aircraft|cargo]] or [[Air charter|charter flights]] to the airport, and worsening air traffic congestion, it was decided to construct a new airport to serve Istanbul. Furthermore, due to a lack of slot capacity and parking spaces, some of [[Turkish Airlines]]' aircraft were based in [[Sabiha G\u00f6k\u00e7en Airport]]{{citation needed|date=May 2017}} which itself is already at maximum terminal capacity of 25 million passengers, and handled 28 million passengers in 2015 after posting traffic growth rates averaging over 20% a year since 2013.{{citation needed|date=May 2017}}\n\nAtat\u00fcrk Airport was [[List of the busiest airports in Europe|one of the busiest airports in Europe]]. Since 2013, it has ranked among the five busiest airports in Europe by passenger traffic. In 2017, the two Istanbul airports handled over 100 million passengers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ataturk.dhmi.gov.tr/getBinaryFile.aspx?Type=13&dosyaID=3&IstatistikID=129|title=Turkish Airport Traffic Statistics|last=|first=|date=|website=DHMI Turkey|access-date=18 March 2016}}</ref> In terms of area airports, the six [[London]]-area airports [[List of the busiest airports in Europe|serve more than 150 million passengers a year]], while the three [[Paris]]-area airports [[List of the busiest airports in Europe|serve around 100 million passengers a year]].\n\n=== Location ===\nIt was decided to construct the new airport at the intersection of roads to [[Arnavutk\u00f6y (district)|Arnavutk\u00f6y]], [[G\u00f6kt\u00fcrk, Istanbul|G\u00f6kt\u00fcrk]], and [[\u00c7atalca]], north of central Istanbul and between the [[Black Sea]] coast towns of {{Interlanguage link|Yenik\u00f6y, Arnavutk\u00f6y|tr||lt=Yenik\u00f6y|WD=}}, [[Tayakad\u0131n, Arnavutk\u00f6y|Tayakad\u0131n]] and Akp\u0131nar. The area is a {{convert|7659|ha|acre|adj=on}} region near [[Lake Terkos]]. Some {{convert|6172|ha|acre}} of this area was state-owned forest. The distance between Istanbul Airport and Atat\u00fcrk Airport is approximately {{convert|35|km|mi|abbr=on|sp=us}}. The area encompassed old [[open-pit mining|open-pit coal mines]], which were later filled with soil.<ref name=\"hdn\"/>\n\nAccording to the Environmental Impact Assessment (\u00c7ED) report published in April 2013, there were a total of 2,513,341 trees in the area and 657,950 of them would need to be cut indispensably, while 1,855,391 trees would be moved to new places. However, the [[Ministry of Forest and Water Management (Turkey)|Ministry of Forest and Water Management]] claimed the exact number of trees cut and moved would only be revealed after construction was complete.<ref name=\"hdn\"/>\n\n===Construction===\n[[File:Istanbul International Airport Location Map (English).png|thumb|Location of ''Istanbul Airport'' relative to the city center of [[Istanbul]], as well as the city's other two airports]]\n\nThe tender for construction and operation of the facility until mid-2020s was held on May 3, 2013.<ref name=\"star\">{{ cite web |publisher=[[Star (Turkish newspaper)|Star]]|url=http://haber.stargazete.com/ekonomi/3-havalimaninda-tarih-belli-oldu/haber-721825 |title=D\u00fcnyan\u0131n en b\u00fcy\u00fck havaliman\u0131 \u0130stanbul'a yap\u0131l\u0131yor |date=2013-01-24 |accessdate=2013-01-24 }}</ref> The project is made up of four construction stages. If all stages are completed, the airport will reach a capacity of 200 million passengers, which would have made it the biggest in the world at the time of planning. The first stage of construction was planned to finish within 42 months of the handover of the land. The total project cost is expected to be approximately \u20ac7 billion, excluding financing costs. The construction and operation consortium has been guaranteed 342 million passengers in 12 years by the government.{{citation needed|date=May 2017}}\n\nThe design team was led by London-based Grimshaw<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://grimshaw.global/projects/istanbul-new-airport/|title=Istanbul New Airport|last=Architects|first=Grimshaw|website=grimshaw.global|access-date=2018-10-02}}</ref> and also included the Norway-based Nordic Office of Architecture and London studio Haptic.{{Citation needed|date=October 2018}}\n\nAt the bidding session on May 3, 2013, only four out of fifteen Turkish and two foreign companies that were qualified as bidders showed up. The Turkish joint venture consortium of [[Cengiz Holding|Cengiz]]-Kolin-[[Limak Holding|Limak]]-Mapa-[[Kalyon Group|Kalyon]] won the tender, and were obliged to pay the government [[euro sign|\u20ac]]26.142 billion including [[value-added tax]] for a 25-year lease starting from 2018. The completion date of the construction's first stage was officially set for 2018 \u2013 42 months after the finalization of the tender's approval.<ref name=\"hdn\">{{cite news |url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/consortium-wins-istanbul-airport-tender-for-221-billion-euros.aspx?pageID=238&nID=46153&NewsCatID=344 |newspaper=[[H\u00fcrriyet Daily News]] |title=Consortium wins Istanbul airport tender for 22.1 billion euros |date=2013-05-03 |accessdate=2013-05-03 }}</ref>\n\nThe groundbreaking ceremony took place on 7 June 2014,<ref name=\":0\">[https://www.welt.de/newsticker/dpa_nt/infoline_nt/wirtschaft_nt/article128833627/Grundsteinlegung-fuer-Mega-Flughafen-in-Istanbul.html ''Grundsteinlegung f\u00fcr Mega-Flughafen in Istanbul.''] welt.de, 7. Juni 2014; retrieved, 8 June 2014</ref> though construction only started in May 2015 after the land was officially handed over.<ref name=constr>{{cite news|title=Construction of new Istanbul airport officially starts under shadow of challenges, questions|url=http://www.turkishweekly.net/2015/07/18/news/construction-of-new-istanbul-airport-officially-starts-under-shadow-of-challenges-questions/|accessdate=21 July 2015|date=18 July 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150802094610/http://www.turkishweekly.net/2015/07/18/news/construction-of-new-istanbul-airport-officially-starts-under-shadow-of-challenges-questions/|archivedate=2 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe inauguration of the airport took place on the planned date of 29 October 2018. It was reported that the first test landing at the airport would take place on February 26, 2018; however, the first landing took place on 20 June 2018.<ref name=\"openingdateoct\">[https://www.yeniasir.com.tr/ekonomi/2018/02/08/ilk-yolcusu-cumhurbaskani-erdogan-olacak - \"Istanbul Grand Airport to open in October 2018\"] (German) 6 October 2017</ref> Testing of navigational and electronic systems with [[General Directorate of State Airports|DHM\u0130]] aircraft had begun on 15 May 2018.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.trthaber.com/haber/ekonomi/3-havalimaninin-yuzde-90i-tamamlandi-367379.html|title=3. Havaliman\u0131'n\u0131n y\u00fczde 90'\u0131 tamamland\u0131|date=27 May 2018|website=trthaber.com|language=Turkish|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180701140248/https://www.trthaber.com/haber/ekonomi/3-havalimaninin-yuzde-90i-tamamlandi-367379.html|archive-date=2018-07-01|access-date=1 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe control tower is in the shape of the Turkish national flower, the [[tulip]].<ref>{{cite magazine|author=Suri, Charu|url=https://www.architecturaldigest.com/story/istanbul-new-airport|title=This New Airport Is Larger Than Manhattan|magazine=[[Architectural Digest]]|date=2018-10-25|accessdate=2019-06-15}}</ref>\n\n===Project stages===\nThe construction of the airport is taking place in several stages, expanding the airport and its facilities over time.<ref name=\"star\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/business/2017/11/10/istanbuls-third-airport-71-pct-completed|title=Istanbul's third airport 71 pct completed|website=Daily Sabah|access-date=2017-11-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://igairport.com/en/istanbul-new-airport/construction/about-the-construction|title=\u0130GA - About the Construction|website=igairport.com|access-date=2018-03-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180328103248/http://igairport.com/en/istanbul-new-airport/construction/about-the-construction|archive-date=2018-03-28|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.igairport.com/istanbul-yeni-havalimani/insaat/asamalar|title=\u0130GA - A\u015famalar|website=www.igairport.com|access-date=2018-03-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180430202254/http://www.igairport.com/istanbul-yeni-havalimani/insaat/asamalar|archive-date=30 April 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe first stage consists of the main terminal, with an annual passenger capacity of 90 million and an area of {{convert|1440000|m2|sqft|abbr=on}} \u2013&nbsp;making it the world's largest [[airport terminal]] building under a single roof,<ref name=\"igaconstr\">{{cite web |title=Construction - \u0130GA |url=https://www.igairport.com/en/about-iga/construction |website=igairport.com |accessdate=6 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190401162826/https://www.igairport.com/en/about-iga/construction |archive-date=1 April 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref> despite [[Dubai International Airport Terminal 3]] having a larger floor area at {{convert|1713000|m2|sqft|abbr=on}} due to tunnels connecting its two concourses. There will also be two pairs of parallel [[runway]]s connected to eight parallel [[taxiway]]s to the west of the main terminal, approximately {{convert|4000000|m2|sqft|abbr=on}} of apron space, and an indoor [[Parking lot|car-park]] with a capacity of 12,000 vehicles. In addition, the airport will feature three technical blocks for repairs, maintenance, and fueling, as well as an air traffic control tower, eight ramp control towers, and hangars for cargo and [[general aviation]] aircraft.<ref name=igaphases>{{cite web |title=Phases - \u0130GA |url=https://www.igairport.com/en/about-iga/construction/phases |website=igairport.com |accessdate=6 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190401143516/https://www.igairport.com/en/about-iga/construction/phases |archive-date=1 April 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Several other services are also to be in operation, including hospitals, frequent-flyer and VIP lounges, prayer rooms, convention centers, and hotels; some of these are expected to form part of the ''Istanbul Airport City'' project.<ref>{{cite web |title=Istanbul Airport City - \u0130GA |url=https://www.igairport.com/en/istanbul-airport/istanbul-airport-city |website=igairport.com |accessdate=6 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe second stage will add a third independent runway to the east of the main terminal, as well as a fourth remote runway with an east-west heading and additional taxiways and apron areas. The third stage is planned to add a second passenger terminal with a capacity of 60 million annual passengers and an estimated area of around {{convert|960000|m2|sqft|abbr=on}}, as well as an additional runway and a new support facilities area.\nThe final and fourth stage of expansion will, along with adding another runway, allow for the construction of [[satellite terminal]]s with a combined capacity of 50 million passengers and area of up to {{convert|800000|m2|sqft|abbr=on}} if needed.<ref name=\"igaphases\" />\n\nOnce fully completed by 2025, the airport will have six sets of runways (eight in total), 16 taxiways, and a total annual passenger capacity of 150 million passengers.<ref name=\"igaconstr\" /><ref>{{cite web|last1=Ay|first1=Hasan|title=Havaliman\u0131 de\u011fil zafer an\u0131t\u0131|url=http://www.sabah.com.tr/Gundem/2014/06/08/havalimani-degil-zafer-aniti|website=sabah.com.tr|publisher=Sabah|accessdate=8 June 2014}}</ref> If fully expanded to a capacity of 200 million, the airport will exhibit four terminal buildings with interconnecting rail access that combine for a total indoor area of {{convert|3200000|m2|sqft|abbr=on}}. The airport will also have a {{convert|6500000|m2|sqft|abbr=on}} apron with a parking capacity of 500 aircraft, VIP lounges, cargo and general aviation facilities, a state palace, and indoor and outdoor parking that can accommodate up to 70,000 cars. A medical center, [[aircraft rescue and firefighting]] stations, hotels, convention centers, power plants, and [[wastewater treatment]] facilities will also be built.\n\n=== Controversies ===\nThe Turkish Chamber of Environmental Engineers (\u00c7MO) took the project tender to court on grounds that the project violated the existing legislation for the preparation of the Environmental Impact Assessment (\u00c7ED) report.<ref name=\"hdn\" /> In February 2014, an Istanbul administrative court ordered construction of the airport to be suspended.<ref name=\"todayszaman\">{{cite news|url=http://www.todayszaman.com/news-339045-istanbul-court-orders-suspension-of-3rd-airports-construction.html|title=\u0130stanbul court orders suspension of 3rd airport's construction|date=2014-02-10|newspaper=Today's Zaman|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140226030448/http://www.todayszaman.com//news-339045-istanbul-court-orders-suspension-of-3rd-airports-construction.html|archivedate=2014-02-26|url-status=dead|accessdate=2014-06-08}}</ref> However, the groundbreaking ceremony took place a few months later, on 7 June 2014.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nA report published in Turkish newspaper ''[[Cumhuriyet]]'' in February 2018 claimed that more than 400 workers had been killed during the construction of the airport, with accidents killing three to four workers every week, and families of the killed workers being paid to remain silent about the incidents.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.augsburger-allgemeine.de/politik/Staunen-und-Sterben-auf-dem-neuen-Mega-Flughafen-in-Istanbul-id44313116.html|title=Staunen und Sterben auf dem neuen Mega-Flughafen in Istanbul|last=G\u00fcsten|first=Susanne|date=25 February 2018|work=[[Augsburger Allgemeine]]|access-date=26 February 2018|location=|language=German|trans-title=Amazement and dying at the new mega-airport in Istanbul}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://thearabweekly.com/mega-airport-project-turkeys-istanbul-rocked-deaths-dozens-workers|title=Mega airport project in Turkey\u2019s Istanbul rocked by deaths of dozens of workers|last=Seibert|first=Thomas|date=25 February 2018|work=The Arab Weekly|access-date=31 October 2018}}</ref> Turkish daily ''[[Evrensel]]'' also alleged that fatal accidents continued to occur.<ref name=\":2\" /> This prompted [[Republican People's Party (Turkey)|opposition MP]] [[Veli A\u011fbaba]] to submit a written questionnaire to the [[Grand National Assembly of Turkey|Turkish parliament]] on 13 February 2018. In response, the [[Ministry of Labour and Social Security (Turkey)|Turkish Ministry of Labour and Social Security]] claimed that there were only 27 fatalities during the construction of the airport.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/turkish-government-says-27-workers-killed-in-istanbuls-third-airport-construction-127312|title=Turkish government says 27 workers killed in Istanbul\u2019s third airport construction|last=Boyac\u0131o\u011flu|first=Hacer|date=14 February 2018|work=[[H\u00fcrriyet]]|access-date=26 February 2018|location=}}</ref> In October 2019, UK publications ''[[Construction News]]'' and ''[[Architects' Journal]]'' published a joint investigation into fatalities at the airport - nicknamed by workers \"the cemetery\" as so many have died.<ref name=\"Garnerp-10Oct2019\">{{cite news |last1=Garner-Purkis |first1=Zac |last2=Hurst |first2=Will |title=Investigation: the human cost of building the world\u2019s biggest airport |url=https://www.architectsjournal.co.uk/10044751.article |accessdate=10 October 2019 |work=Architects' Journal |date=10 October 2019}}</ref> By this point, the official death toll was 55, but unofficial estimates suggested the figure could \"be higher than 400\". Four architects worked on the airport's design, three of them UK-based: [[Grimshaw Architects]], [[Scott Brownrigg]] and Haptic Architects.<ref name=\"Garnerp-10Oct2019\"/>\n\nMass worker protests broke out on 14 September 2018 after a bus carrying workers crashed, injuring 17. Complaints by workers included poor living conditions in \"vermin-infested dormitories\", issues in transportation that had left them stranded under the rain or on site during holidays, and long delays in payments, among others.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://ahvalnews.com/third-airport/workers-forced-build-new-airport-under-gendarmerie-supervision-istanbul|title=Workers forced to build new airport under gendarmerie supervision in Istanbul|last=|first=|date=2018-09-17|work=Ahval|access-date=2018-10-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181015095150/https://ahvalnews.com/third-airport/workers-forced-build-new-airport-under-gendarmerie-supervision-istanbul|archive-date=2018-10-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/turkce/haberler-turkiye-45559105|title=3. Havaliman\u0131 eylemleri: \u0130\u015f\u00e7iler ne talep ediyor, ana firma \u0130GA taleplere ne diyor?|last=\u00d6zt\u00fcrk|first=Fundanur|date=2018-09-20|work=BBC News T\u00fcrk\u00e7e|access-date=2018-10-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181015095522/https://www.bbc.com/turkce/haberler-turkiye-45559105|archive-date=2018-10-15|language=tr}}</ref> Police and [[Gendarmerie General Command|gendarmerie]] forces were called in and workers eventually returned to work under alleged threats of arrest or further withholding of wages.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nOn 19 December 2018, part of the airport site was flooded after heavy rain.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ahvalnews.com/istanbul-new-airport/istanbuls-new-airport-site-floods-after-heavy-rain|title=Istanbul\u2019s new airport site floods after heavy rain|date=19 December 2018|accessdate=20 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, the MP [[Meral Dan\u0131\u015f Be\u015fta\u015f|Meral Dan\u0131\u015f Besta\u015f]] demanded an explanation for why the new translation service of 36 languages at Istanbul Airport did not include Kurdish, a language spoken by a large minority within Turkey.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ahvalnews.com/turkey-kurds/kurdish-absent-istanbul-airports-instant-translation-service|title=Kurdish absent from Istanbul Airport\u2019s instant translation service|website=Ahval|language=en|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref>\n\n=== Operations ===\nThe opening ceremony took place on 29 October 2018, scheduled so as to coincide with the 95th [[Republic Day (Turkey)|anniversary of the proclamation of the Turkish Republic]].<ref name=\"HDN-pic\">{{cite news|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/photo-new-istanbul-airport-inaugurated-with-ceremony-138359|title='Istanbul Airport' inaugurated as Erdo\u011fan says Atat\u00fcrk Airport will remain in downsized form|author=|date=29 October 2018|newspaper=[[H\u00fcrriyet Daily News]]|accessdate=29 October 2018}}</ref> The airport had been unofficially known as 'Istanbul New Airport' during construction - the new official name of 'Istanbul Airport' was announced at the opening ceremony. The first flight from the airport was [[Turkish Airlines]] flight TK2124 to the Turkish capital [[Esenbo\u011fa International Airport|Ankara]] on 31 October 2018.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/first-flight-departs-from-istanbuls-new-airport/2018/10/31/94f625c6-dce9-11e8-8bac-bfe01fcdc3a6_story.html?|title=First flight departs from Istanbul\u2019s new airport|newspaper=The Washington Post|accessdate=2 November 2018}}</ref> On 1 November 2018, five daily flights began to arrive and depart from the airport: from [[Esenboga Airport|Ankara]], [[Antalya Airport|Antalya]], [[Baku Airport|Baku]], [[Ercan International Airport|North Nicosia]], and [[Adnan Menderes Airport|\u0130zmir]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.haberturk.com/son-dakika-yeni-havalimani-nda-thynin-ilk-ucus-fiyatlari-belli-oldu-2175382-ekonomi|title=Yeni Havaliman\u0131'nda THY\u2019nin ilk u\u00e7u\u015f fiyatlar\u0131 belli oldu|website=Habert\u00fcrk}}</ref> followed by [[Adana]] and [[Trabzon]] starting in December.\n\nBefore the full transfer, all flights were operated exclusively by [[Turkish Airlines]]. Regularly scheduled flights to all of the new airport's destinations continued to depart from Atat\u00fcrk and Sabiha G\u00f6k\u00e7en airports alongside these trial flights. It was originally planned that on 31 December 2018, all equipment from Atat\u00fcrk Airport would be transferred to the new airport via the [[Otoyol 7|O-7 Motorway]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.kokpit.aero/dhmi-yeni-havalimani-tasinma|title=Kokpit.aero\u2019nun dedi\u011fi \u00e7\u0131kt\u0131: \u0130stanbul Yeni Havaliman\u0131 i\u00e7in ta\u015f\u0131nma tarihi a\u00e7\u0131kland\u0131|date=2018-10-05|website=www.kokpit.aero|language=tr|access-date=2018-10-06}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-turkey-airport/new-istanbul-airport-to-only-open-fully-at-end-of-year-paper-idUSKCN1MN0H7|title=New Istanbul airport to only open fully at end of year: paper|last=|first=|date=2018-10-13|work=Reuters|access-date=2018-10-15}}</ref> As of 17 January 2019, the transfer phase was set to start 1 March 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.public.nm.eurocontrol.int/PUBPORTAL/gateway/spec/PORTAL.22.5.0.3.6/_res/6597/PROGRAMME.PDF?APPID=headline_news|title=TRANSFER PROGRAMME FOR ISTANBUL AIRPORT (LTFM)|date=17 January 2019|website=Eurocontrol NOP}}</ref> However, on 25 February, the transfer phase was moved a fourth time to 5 April 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.public.nm.eurocontrol.int/PUBPORTAL/gateway/spec/PORTAL.22.5.0.3.6/_res/6597/Transfer.pdf?APPID=headline_news|title=TRANSFER PROGRAMME FOR ISTANBUL AIRPORT (LTFM)|date=25 February 2019|website=Eurocontrol NOP}}</ref>\n\nThe full transfer of all scheduled [[Commercial aviation|commercial passenger flights]] from [[Istanbul Atat\u00fcrk Airport]] to the new Istanbul Airport took place on 6 April 2019 between 02:00 and 14:00. Hundreds of trucks carried more than 10,000 pieces of equipment, each weighing about 44 tons were moved to the new airport over 41 hours.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.de/new-istanbul-airport-turkish-airlines-moves-flights-41-hours-2019-4|title=Turkey's national carrier moved all its flights from Istanbul's old airport to its shiny replacement in a single, stressful, 41-hour 'big bang'|last=Insider|first=Alexandra Ma, Business|website=Business Insider Deutschland|language=de|access-date=2019-04-09}}</ref> [[Istanbul Atat\u00fcrk Airport]]'s [[IATA code]] IST was also transferred to the new airport.\n\n== Facilities ==\n[[File:Istanbul Airport Gates ENG.png|thumb|The different gate areas of Istanbul Airport]]\nThe airport currently has one terminal in service for domestic and international flights and four runways that are currently in operation. The two 17/35 runways are both 4,100 metres (13,451 feet) long, while the 16/34 runways are both 3,750 metres (12,303 feet) long. Runways 17L/35R and 16R/34L are 60 metres (197 feet) wide, while 17R/35L and 16L/34R are 45 metres (148 feet) wide. All runway surfaces are [[asphalt]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pbs.twimg.com/media/DqxXm0DWwAAmCyZ.jpg:large|title=LTFM Chart|date=2018-10-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181106203835/https://pbs.twimg.com/media/DqxXm0DWwAAmCyZ.jpg:large|archive-date=2018-11-06|url-status=}}</ref>\n\n=== Concourses ===\nThe airport features a total of five concourses lettered A, B, D, F, and G with a total of 143 passenger boarding bridges. Concourse G, which is located in the southeast, is reserved solely for domestic flights. Three passenger boarding bridges of Concourse F which is directly to the north of Concourse G has also been allocated for domestic flights. Concourses A, B, D, and F will be used for international flights. The C and E concourses connect directly to the main terminal and are therefore not independent concourses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.istanbulhavalimani.com/en/passenger/airport-guide/airport-map|title=Istanbul Airport Map}}</ref>\n\n=== Security ===\n3,500 security personnel and a total of 1,850 [[General Directorate of Security (Turkey)|police]], including 750 [[immigration officer]]s, are expected to provide the airport's security.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.haberturk.com/istanbul-yeni-havalimani-nda-1850-polis-gorev-yapacak-1871373-ekonomi|title=29 Ekim\u2019de ilk etab\u0131 a\u00e7\u0131lacak|last=|first=|date=2018-11-03|work=Habert\u00fcrk|access-date=2018-11-06|archive-url=https://archive.today/20181106212516/https://www.haberturk.com/istanbul-yeni-havalimani-nda-1850-polis-gorev-yapacak-1871373-ekonomi|archive-date=6 November 2018|language=tr-TR|url-status=live}}</ref> The site's perimeter will be protected using ground radar, fixed [[Closed-circuit television camera|CCTV cameras]] every 60 meters, [[pan\u2013tilt\u2013zoom camera]]s every 360 meters, [[Thermographic camera|thermal cameras]] and [[fiber optic sensor]]s every 720 meters. The active terminal building uses up to 9,000 CCTV cameras.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ntv.com.tr/galeri/teknoloji/ilk-kez-istanbul-havalimaninda-kullanilacak,jIyImduxHUyM8EP5bkGBSA|title=\u0130lk kez \u0130stanbul Havaliman\u0131'nda kullan\u0131lacak|date=2018-11-03|website=NTV|archive-url=https://archive.today/20181106212754/https://www.ntv.com.tr/galeri/teknoloji/ilk-kez-istanbul-havalimaninda-kullanilacak,jIyImduxHUyM8EP5bkGBSA|archive-date=6 November 2018|url-status=live|access-date=2018-11-06}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==Airlines and destinations==\n===Passenger===\n{{Airport destination list\n|[[Aegean Airlines]]| [[Athens International Airport|Athens]]\n<!-- -->\n|[[Aeroflot]]| [[Sheremetyevo International Airport|Moscow\u2013Sheremetyevo]]\n<!-- -->\n|[[Afriqiyah Airways]]| [[Al Abraq International Airport|Bayda]], [[Mitiga International Airport|Tripoli\u2013Mitiga]]\n<!-- -->\n|[[Air Albania]]| [[Tirana International Airport N\u00ebn\u00eb Tereza|Tirana]]\n<!-- -->\n|[[Air Alg\u00e9rie]]| [[Houari Boumediene Airport|Algiers]], [[Rabah Bitat Airport|Annaba]], [[Mohamed Boudiaf International Airport|Constantine]], [[Oran Airport|Oran]]\n<!-- -->\n|[[Air Astana]]| [[Almaty International Airport|Almaty]], [[Atyrau Airport|Atyrau]], [[Nursultan Nazarbayev International Airport|Nur-Sultan]]\n<!-- -->\n|[[Air France]]| [[Charles de Gaulle Airport|Paris\u2013Charles de Gaulle]]\n<!-- -->\n|[[Air Moldova]]| [[Chisinau International Airport|Chi\u015fin\u0103u]]\n<!-- -->\n|[[Air Serbia]]| [[Belgrade Nikola Tesla Airport|Belgrade]] \n<!-- -->\n|[[All Nippon Airways]]| [[Haneda Airport|Tokyo\u2013Haneda]] (begins 6 July 2020)<ref>https://www.routesonline.com/news/29/breaking-news/289028/ana-to-launch-tokyo-haneda-istanbul-route-shifts